{"title_page": "Torra d'Omigna", "text_new": "{{short description|Genoese tower in Corsica}}\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n|name=Tower of Omigna\n|native_name=Torra d'Omigna\n|native_language=Corsican\n|image=Corse-Cargese-Tour Omigna.jpg\n|caption=\n|designation1=Monument historique\n|designation1_date=8 March 1991\n|designation1_partof=\n|designation1_number=[http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_98=REF&VALUE_98=PA00099136 PA00099136] \n|designation1_criteria=\n|designation1_type=\n|designation1_free1name=\n|designation1_free1value=\n|designation2=\n|designation2_date=\n|designation2_number=\n|designation2_offname=\n|location=\n|built=1605&ndash;1606\n| restored=2009\n|architect=Giacomo della Piana\n|builder=\n|coordinates = {{coord|42|8|47|N|8|33|36|E|type:landmark_region:FR|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin=Corsica\n| map_relief = yes\n}}\n\nThe '''Tower of Omigna''' ({{lang-co|Torra d'Omigna}}) is a ruined [[Genoese tower]] located in the [[communes of France|commune]] of [[Carg\u00e8se]] on the French island of [[Corsica]].\n\nThe tower was built between 1605 and 1606 under the direction of Giacomo della Piana. It was one of a series of coastal defences built by the [[Republic of Genoa]] between 1530 and 1620 to stem the attacks by [[Barbary pirates]].<ref>{{cite book | last= Graziani | first= Antoine-Marie | contribution= Les ouvrages de d\u00e9fense en Corse contre les Turcs (1530-1650) | editor1-last= Verg\u00e9-Franceschi | editor1-first=Michel | editor2-last= Graziani | editor2-first= Antoine-Marie | year=2000 | title= La guerre de course en M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e (1515-1830) | publisher= Presses de l'Universit\u00e9 Paris IV-Sorbonne | place=Paris | isbn= 2-84050-167-8 | pages=143-144 |language=French }}</ref> In 1991 it was listed as one of the official [[Monument historique|Historical Monuments]] of France.<ref>{{cite web | title= Monuments historiques: Tour d'Omigna  | url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_98=REF&VALUE_98=PA00099136  | publisher=Minist\u00e8re de la culture | language=French | accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref><!--Note that the Conservatoire du littoral doc gives same date but 1993--> \n\nSince 1977 the tower has been owned by a French government agency, the [[Conservatoire du littoral]]. The agency has announced that it plans to purchase {{convert|212|ha|acre}} of the headland and as of 2011 had acquired {{convert|121|ha|acre}}.<ref>{{cite report | title=Catalogue monuments historiques | chapter=Tour Genoise d\u2019Omignia | page=45 | publisher=Conservatoire du littoral, Minist\u00e8re de l'\u00e9cologie, du d\u00e9veloppement durable et de l'\u00e9nergie, R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise | date=July 2011 | accessdate=27 April 2015 | url=http://www.conservatoire-du-littoral.fr/include/viewFile.php?idtf=930&path=e7%2F930_116_Catalogue-Illustre-des-Monuments-HistoriquesB.pdf | language=French }}</ref> The tower was restored in 2009 and visitors can climb up onto the roof terrace.<ref>{{citation |title= March\u00e9s de travaux |publisher=Conservatoire du littoral|url=http://conservatoire-du-littoral.fr/tmp_old/article133CMPann%C3%A9e2009.pdf | language=French | accessdate=4 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAn area of {{convert|255|hectare|acre}} that includes the headland and portions of the adjacent coastline is owned by an agency of the French state, the [[Conservatoire du littoral]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Omigna | url=http://www.conservatoire-du-littoral.fr/siteLittoral/19/28-omigna-2a_corse-du-sud.htm | publisher=Conservatoire du littoral, Minist\u00e8re de l'\u00e9cologie, du d\u00e9veloppement durable et de l'\u00e9nergie | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align     = center\n| image1    = Tour Omigna ASG Corsica 886-1.jpg \n| width1    = 300\n| image2    = Tour Omigna ASG Corsica 886-2.jpg\n| width2    = 149\n| footer    = Drawings from the Genoese archives dating from the time of the tower's construction.\n}}\n\n\n==The 1729 siege of the Tower of Omigna==\nIn 1729, the Greek inhabitants of [[Carg\u00e8se|Paomia]], pursued by the Corsicans of [[Vico, Corse-du-Sud|Vico]] and Niolo who wished to drive them from their lands, took refuge in the Tower of Omigna. Boats from [[Ajaccio]] came to recover the women and children to transport them by sea to Ajaccio, while the men resisted to the siege. Once the women and children were safe, the men made went out, crossed the enemy lines and were able to reach Ajaccio by land.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Le livre d'or de la famille Bonaparte: \u00e9tudes historiques, biographies et portraits Napol\u00e9oniens, publi\u00e9s d'apr\u00e8s des documents authentiques et des notes particuli\u00e8res, Volume 1|publisher=Administration g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des publications illustr\u00e9es, A. Bouret Jne Editeur|year=1855|isbn=|location=|pages=31}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Genoese towers in Corsica]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Omigna, Tower of}}\n[[Category:Towers in Corsica]]\n[[Category:Official historical monuments of Corsica]]\n\n{{Corsica-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genoese tower in Corsica}}\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n|name=Tower of Omigna\n|native_name=Torra d'Omigna\n|native_language=Corsican\n|image=Corse-Cargese-Tour Omigna.jpg\n|caption=\n|designation1=Monument historique\n|designation1_date=8 March 1991\n|designation1_partof=\n|designation1_number=[http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_98=REF&VALUE_98=PA00099136 PA00099136] \n|designation1_criteria=\n|designation1_type=\n|designation1_free1name=\n|designation1_free1value=\n|designation2=\n|designation2_date=\n|designation2_number=\n|designation2_offname=\n|location=\n|built=1605&ndash;1606\n| restored=2009\n|architect=Giacomo della Piana\n|builder=\n|coordinates = {{coord|42|8|47|N|8|33|36|E|type:landmark_region:FR|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin=Corsica\n| map_relief = yes\n}}\n\nThe '''Tower of Omigna''' ({{lang-co|Torra d'Omigna}}) is a ruined [[Genoese tower]] located in the [[communes of France|commune]] of [[Carg\u00e8se]] on the French island of [[Corsica]].\n\nThe tower was built between 1605 and 1606 under the direction of Giacomo della Piana. It was one of a series of coastal defences built by the [[Republic of Genoa]] between 1530 and 1620 to stem the attacks by [[Barbary pirates]].<ref>{{cite book | last= Graziani | first= Antoine-Marie | contribution= Les ouvrages de d\u00e9fense en Corse contre les Turcs (1530-1650) | editor1-last= Verg\u00e9-Franceschi | editor1-first=Michel | editor2-last= Graziani | editor2-first= Antoine-Marie | year=2000 | title= La guerre de course en M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e (1515-1830) | publisher= Presses de l'Universit\u00e9 Paris IV-Sorbonne | place=Paris | isbn= 2-84050-167-8 | pages=143-144 |language=French }}</ref> In 1991 it was listed as one of the official [[Monument historique|Historical Monuments]] of France.<ref>{{cite web | title= Monuments historiques: Tour d'Omigna  | url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_98=REF&VALUE_98=PA00099136  | publisher=Minist\u00e8re de la culture | language=French | accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref><!--Note that the Conservatoire du littoral doc gives same date but 1993--> \n\nSince 1977 the tower has been owned by a French government agency, the [[Conservatoire du littoral]]. The agency has announced that it plans to purchase {{convert|212|ha|acre}} of the headland and as of 2011 had acquired {{convert|121|ha|acre}}.<ref>{{cite report | title=Catalogue monuments historiques | chapter=Tour Genoise d\u2019Omignia | page=45 | publisher=Conservatoire du littoral, Minist\u00e8re de l'\u00e9cologie, du d\u00e9veloppement durable et de l'\u00e9nergie, R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise | date=July 2011 | accessdate=27 April 2015 | url=http://www.conservatoire-du-littoral.fr/include/viewFile.php?idtf=930&path=e7%2F930_116_Catalogue-Illustre-des-Monuments-HistoriquesB.pdf | language=French }}</ref> The tower was restored in 2009 and visitors can climb up onto the roof terrace.<ref>{{citation |title= March\u00e9s de travaux |publisher=Conservatoire du littoral|url=http://conservatoire-du-littoral.fr/tmp_old/article133CMPann%C3%A9e2009.pdf | language=French | accessdate=4 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAn area of {{convert|255|hectare|acre}} that includes the headland and portions of the adjacent coastline is owned by an agency of the French state, the [[Conservatoire du littoral]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Omigna | url=http://www.conservatoire-du-littoral.fr/siteLittoral/19/28-omigna-2a_corse-du-sud.htm | publisher=Conservatoire du littoral, Minist\u00e8re de l'\u00e9cologie, du d\u00e9veloppement durable et de l'\u00e9nergie | accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align     = center\n| image1    = Tour Omigna ASG Corsica 886-1.jpg \n| width1    = 300\n| image2    = Tour Omigna ASG Corsica 886-2.jpg\n| width2    = 149\n| footer    = Drawings from the Genoese archives dating from the time of the tower's construction.\n}}\n\n\n==The Siege go the Tower of Omigna==\nIn 1729, the Greek inhabitants of [[Carg\u00e8se|Paomia]], pursued by the Corsicans of [[Vico, Corse-du-Sud|Vico]] and Niolo who wished to drive them from their lands, took refuge in the Tower of Omigna. Boats from [[Ajaccio]] came to recover the women and children to transport them by sea to Ajaccio, while the men resisted to the siege. Once the women and children were safe, the men made went out, crossed the enemy lines and were able to reach Ajaccio by land.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Le livre d'or de la famille Bonaparte: \u00e9tudes historiques, biographies et portraits Napol\u00e9oniens, publi\u00e9s d'apr\u00e8s des documents authentiques et des notes particuli\u00e8res, Volume 1|publisher=Administration g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des publications illustr\u00e9es, A. Bouret Jne Editeur|year=1855|isbn=|location=|pages=31}}</ref>\n\n==See also